\b0 \cf0 	While I agree with much of MacIntyre\'92s picture of the development of western civilization, the thesis I would like to extract, develop, and defend is this: human practices are necessarily end-directed (teleological). \'93Social teleology\'94 has at least two and possibly three aspects: individual, collective, and human. The first aspect is the end-directed behavior of each agent; the second is the end-directed behavior of social groups, like families, nations, clubs, congregations, and so on. The third, and most objectionable, aspect, is the end-directed activity of our species as a whole. What, if anything, does 
\i every human being 
\i0 intentionally pursue? \
	Let\'92s provide some names to summarize these notions: \

\i 	Human Practical Teleology  Thesis
\i0 : Persons, when we act rationally, act for a reason or reasons and toward some end. \

\i 	Group Practical Teleology Thesis
\i0 : Groups, when we act rationally, act for reasons and toward some end(s). \

\i 	Human Natural Teleology Thesis. 
\i0 Insofar as an agent is a human, that agent acts for a reason, both as an individual and in social groups. \
	In the next chapter, I shall defend one version of the more controversial and less popular 
\i Natural Teleology Thesis
\i0 : At least some parts of nature (that is, non-human nature) are necessarily end-directed. But more on that later. \
	To defend social teleology we have to point out what phenomena up for explanation, and clarify why social teleological explanations are the best. That I shall attempt in the first section. In the second section, I tackle an important piece of this defense: a defense of the very notion of a human nature. Finally, if there is such a thing as human nature, then it is reasonable to query whether human nature is part of \'93nature\'94 as a whole \'97 what is our relationship to 
\i the rest 
\i0 of nature? A very old and very widespread belief is that humans are sui generis and somehow \'93special.\'94 Is this belief mistaken, a superstition, an instance of magic-thinking, a holdover from pre-Darwinian  or pre-scientific thinking? I tackle these questions in the third section. \
