In the second section, I tackle an important piece of this defense: a defense of the very notion of a human nature. \
	
\i0 Sarte famously taught that human beings have no inherent nature. There are no \'93built-in\'94 limits to what we can do and become. We create ourselves 
\i ex nihilo. \
	
\i0 As I understand the term, a nature refers to just about the same entity as another important (and highly contentious) modern term: species. A nature is a formal property or cluster of formal properties that define a given thing. To say that \'93chairs have legs 
\i by nature
\i0 \'94 is to say that chairs by virtue of being 
\i what they are 
\i0 have four legs (which may be false). To say that bucks have horns is to identify a formal property all bucks share. \
	Theories of 
\i human
\i0  nature give various weights to biological, psychological, intellectual, and spiritual properties of human beings. All humans are rational animals; all humans are images of God; all humans are rational, social animals; humans are highly evolved animals of the species 
\i homo sapiens sapiens; 
\i0 all \
	A nature defines what a thing is across time. An acorn is not an oak tree \'97 not a mature oak tree yet \'97 but an acorn has the same nature as the mature oak tree. 
\i \
	
\i0 Natures are discovered more or less empirically. We examine tendencies of a given organism and infer to such-and-such a nature. The posited nature is a formal cause that explains those tendencies. \
	On my view, human nature is a discernible form defined by a set of biological and psychological properties. 
